value.value: The anatomical cluster that is composed of epithelial cell(s) that secrete or excrete materials not related to their ordinary metabolic needs.
The lobe of the labium that is limited posteroproximally by the prementum, anteroproximally by the fold traversing the salivary orifice and laterally by the paraglossae.
The labial muscle that arises on the ventral part of the prementum, laterally to the ventral premento-salivarial muscle and inserts on the anterior glossal plate.
The groove that is located between the spiracle and the anterior margin of abdominal tergum 2.
The compound organ that makes gametes.
The apophysis that is located ventromedially on the proximal margin of the cupula and is the site of insertion of the lateral S9-cupulal muscle.
The sclerite that is located distally of the cupula and dorsolaterally of the volsella, surrounds the aedeagus dorsolaterally and does not connected to any sclerite distally.
The conjunctiva that is located at the distal apex of the harpe.
The anatomical cluster that is composed of the gonostipites, volsellae and harpes.
The male genitalia muscle that arises from the basiura and inserts on the endophallus.
The sclerite that is located on the distoventral part of the gonostyle/volsella complex, and is articulated with the more proximal sclerites of the gononstyle/volsella complex.

The sclerite that is located dorsolaterally on the gonostyle/volsella complex, is connected to the distal margin of the cupula, to the proximal margin of the harpe, and to the lateral margin of the volsella.
The apodeme that is located proximally on the ventral part of the gonostipes.
The male genitalia muscle that arises proximally from the ventral part of the gonostipes and inserts on the volsella at the border between the gono- and parossiculi.
The anatomical cluster that is composed of sclerites located distally of the cupula dorsolaterally of the volsella, and that surround the aedeagus.
The carina that is transverse and posteriorly directed laterally and is located on the abdominal tergite.
The seta that is located on the anterior margin of the hind wing and interlocks with the recurved posterior edge of the fore wing in Hymenoptera during flight, making them functionally one winged.
The sclerite that is located distally on the gonostyle/volsella complex and does not connect to the cupula, and does not connect to the volsella by conjunctiva or muscles.
The male genitalia muscle that arises form the harpe and inserts on the gonomacula.
The tagma that is located anterior to the thorax.
The anatomical cluster that is composed of the cranium and compound eye cuticle.
The leg that is located on the metathorax.
The wing that is located on the metathorax.
The anatomical cluster that is composed of median plates.
The sclerite that articulates with the proximal end of the costal vein.
The sclerite that is connected to the lateral margin of the metanotum and bears the anterior metanotal wing process.
The multi-cellular organism that is classified in Hymenoptera.
The carina that extends on the vertex between the outer orbits.
The anatomical space that is delimited anteriorly by the clypeus and posteriorly by the labrum.
The ligament that connects the proximolateral margin of the prementum with the proximal part of the ligula.
The area that is delimited proximally by the proximal margin of the sitophore, distally by the salivarial orifice.
The abdominal sternum that is the posteriormost visible sclerite located ventrally in the abdomen.

The area that extends on the posterior (ventral) margin of the oral foramen along the site of attachments of the conjunctiva connecting the cranium with the maxillae and is delimited laterally by the pleurostomal fossa.
The subforaminal bridge that is delimited laterally by the dorsally extended hypostomal carina.
The carina that delimits the hypostoma from the cranium.
The sulcus that extends along the posteroventral margin of the cranium between the pleurostomal fossae and delimits the hypostoma.
The projection that is located on the posterolateral margin of the oral foramen at the junction of the hypostoma and the pleurostomal fossa.
The groove that does not correspond to a ridge.

The anatomical cluster that is composed of a ridge that extends along the margin of a sclerite and the marginal area of the sclerite delimited from the sclerite by the ridge articulating with the inflection of another sclerite.
The line that extends along the border between the eye and face.
The tarsal plantula that arises medially on the tarsomere.
The anatomical system that forms the covering layer of the animal, ectodermal in origin and composed of epidermal cells producing the cuticle.
The area that is elevated and extends between the antennal rims.
The median sulcus of the mesonotum between the anterior margin of the mesoscutellar-axillar complex and the anterior margin of the mesoscutellum.
The area that is located between the acetabular carina and the ventral mesopleural carina.

The compound organ that functions as producer and transporter of sperm, spermatophore and semen, composed of the testes, vas deferens, accessory glands and ductus ejaculatorius. Ecto- and mesodermal in origin.
The ridge that corresponds to the metascutellar arm.
The pit that is located on the upper face between lateral ocelli and corresponds internally with a conical apodeme and not the tentorium.
The area that is limited posteriorly by the posterior ocellar line and laterally by the lateral ocellar line.
The seta that is located at the intersection of the margins of three ommatidiae.
